'''Commission on Accreditation for Respiratory Care''' ('''CoARC''') is a [[non-profit]] accreditation organization dedicated to [[Respiratory therapy|Respiratory Care]].<ref name="pmid16477201">{{cite journal| author=Mathews P, Drumheller L, Carlow JJ, with the assistance of the American Association for Respiratory Care. National Board for Respiratory Care. Council on Accreditation of Respiratory Care| title=Respiratory care manpower issues. | journal=Crit Care Med | year= 2006 | volume= 34 | issue= 3 Suppl | pages= S32-45 | pmid=16477201 | doi=10.1097/01.CCM.0000203103.11863.BC | pmc= | url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/elink.fcgi?dbfrom=pubmed&tool=sumsearch.org/cite&retmode=ref&cmd=prlinks&id=16477201  }}</ref><ref name="pmid21535914">{{cite journal| author=Barnes TA, Kacmarek RM, Durbin CG| title=Survey of Respiratory Therapy Education Program Directors in the United States. | journal=Respir Care | year= 2011 | volume=  56| issue=  12| pages=  1906â€“15| pmid=21535914 | doi=10.4187/respcare.01259 | pmc= | url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/elink.fcgi?dbfrom=pubmed&tool=sumsearch.org/cite&retmode=ref&cmd=prlinks&id=21535914  }}</ref>  CoARC accredits degree-granting programs in respiratory care that have undergone a rigorous process of voluntary peer review and have met or exceeded the minimum accreditation Standards as set by the professional association in cooperation with CoARC.<ref name="pmid21535914"/> These programs are granted accreditation status by CoARC, which provides public recognition of such achievement. In 2009 there were over 300 [[List of accredited respiratory therapist programs|accredited programs]] in the United States.<ref name="pmid21535914"/>

